In many cases, young people of non-resident fathers will lose touch with that parent shortly after a divorce.

Growing up with a non-resident father also has other negative effects:

Children of divorced fathers are more likely to suffer from depression and anxiety.

They are less likely to take their final school exams and more likely to be involved in crime.

Birrel, Brodie and Taggart (2002)

We know that the effects of having a non-resident father can be devastating for children.

That’s why this colloquium is about informing and working together, in order to advocate for consistent and evidence-based relationship education programmes for all parents.

For young people experiencing the death of a parent, the effect of this on their well-being needs to be further explored, and appropriate professionals supported and trained to deal with such cases.

Conclusion

To orientate us, I remind us we are at Waitangi, and are descendants of the world’s first people in its earliest migration.

The Māori, inscribed in this rock in Ngāpuhi territory, are our ancestors. This often dominates our concern and pride for our nation.
